sect1.para:
Typically a driver contains the following functionality:

Initialization function XMC_PERI_STATUS_tXMC_PERI_Init(XMC_PERI_t*constperi,constXMC_PERI_CONFIG_tconst*config);

Enable/disable peripheral functions voidXMC_PERI_Enable(XMC_PERI_t*constperi);
voidXMC_PERI_Disable(XMC_PERI_t*constperi);

Connectivity functions voidXMC_PERI_SetInputSource(XMC_PERI_t*constperi,...);

Event handling functions voidXMC_PERI_Enable(XMC_PERI_tconst*peri);
voidXMC_PERI_Disable(XMC_PERI_tconst*peri);
voidXMC_PERI_EnableEvent(XMC_PERI_tconst*peri);
voidXMC_PERI_DisableEvent(XMC_PERI_tconst*peri);
voidXMC_PERI_TriggerEvent(XMC_PERI_tconst*peri);
uint32_tXMC_PERI_GetEventStatus(XMC_PERI_tconst*peri);
voidXMC_PERI_SetInterruptNode(XMC_PERI_tconst*peri);

Control functions voidXMC_PERI_Start(XMC_PERI_tconst*peri);
voidXMC_PERI_Stop(XMC_PERI_tconst*peri);
voidXMC_PERI_Suspend(XMC_PERI_tconst*peri);
voidXMC_PERI_Resume(XMC_PERI_tconst*peri);

Get/setters functions, run time API to obtain or modify state of peripheral voidXMC_PERI_SetSomething(XMC_PERI_tconst*peri,...);
uint32_tXMC_PERI_GetSomething(XMC_PERI_tconst*peri);

IRQ Handlers are provided which can be used optionally by the user to make easier the coding voidXMC_PERI_IRQHandler(uint32_tsr_num);
